-- ── Discount Bandit ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source, self-hosted price tracker and browser extension that monitors products across Amazon, eBay, and dozens of other stores and alerts you to price drops.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Independent open-source project$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Discount Bandit Review 2026: Free Self-Hosted Price Tracker$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Discount Bandit is a free, open-source, self-hosted price tracker for Amazon, eBay, and more, with a browser extension and Telegram/Ntfy price alerts.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Discount Bandit is an open-source, self-hosted, multi-user price-tracking application paired with a companion browser extension, built for people who want to monitor product prices across multiple online retailers without relying on a third-party commercial service. The project is created and maintained by a developer or small team operating under the handle Cybrarist, who also maintains other self-hosted open-source tools such as Zakaty and InstantLand, and the software is distributed through a GitHub repository (Cybrarist/Discount-Bandit), a public Chrome Web Store listing, and a Docker Hub image for straightforward containerized deployment. Because Discount Bandit is a small, independently maintained open-source project rather than a venture-backed company, there is no publicly documented founding year, headquarters, or formal company structure behind it; it exists as a community-supported codebase rather than a commercial entity. The core idea behind Discount Bandit is straightforward: rather than manually checking product pages for price changes, or trusting a closed commercial browser extension with your shopping data, users self-host the Discount Bandit application on their own server or home lab, add products they want to track, and let the system periodically check prices and notify them when a defined condition is met. The companion browser extension, available for Chrome, lets users add products directly from a retailer's product page without needing to copy and paste URLs into the self-hosted dashboard, streamlining the process of building out a tracked-product list. On the backend, Discount Bandit supports more than 25 built-in retailer integrations, including major platforms such as Amazon, eBay, Walmart, Costco, and AliExpress, and it also allows users to configure unlimited custom stores beyond the built-in list. A notable community-driven aspect of the project is its support for community-contributed store integrations, meaning users can share and reuse scraping configurations for retailers that are not natively supported, extending coverage well beyond the default store list without requiring changes to the core application. Notification delivery is one of Discount Bandit's more flexible features: rather than locking users into a single notification channel, the platform supports Ntfy, Telegram, and Gotify, three widely used self-hosted-friendly notification services, allowing alerts to reach users on their phone or desktop through the channel they already use for other self-hosted tools. Users can configure multiple rules per tracked product, which is useful for accounting for variables like shipping costs or verified-seller status that affect whether a given price is actually a good deal; supported alert criteria include reaching a specific target price, hitting a percentage discount threshold, reaching the lowest price observed within a given time window, changes in stock availability, verification of the seller as an official or authorized retailer, and general price fluctuation alerts. The application also includes basic currency conversion functionality (which requires configuring a third-party currency API key) so that users tracking products priced in different currencies can view converted values in their preferred currency. Discount Bandit is explicitly built as a multi-user system, meaning a single self-hosted instance can serve multiple accounts, each with their own tracked products; administrators can create additional user accounts and set customizable link limits per user, making the tool suitable for shared use among family members or small groups rather than being strictly single-user software. Deployment options reflect the project's self-hosting-first philosophy: it can be installed directly on an operating system, or deployed via Docker, Docker Compose, or Portainer, which are among the most common deployment methods used by home-lab and self-hosted-software communities. A GitHub artisan file in the repository indicates the backend is built on a PHP framework consistent with Laravel-style application structure, which is common among self-hosted web applications favored by that community. Privacy is a significant part of Discount Bandit's value proposition: the project explicitly states that it does not collect any data, does not use any analytics or telemetry service, and does not send data anywhere other than to the retail websites being tracked, which stands in contrast to commercial browser extensions and price-tracking services that often monetize user shopping behavior or browsing data. This privacy-first, self-hosted, and completely free model positions Discount Bandit as a niche alternative to commercial or hosted price-tracking tools such as CamelCamelCamel (which is limited to Amazon), Keepa, and browser extensions like Honey, as well as more general-purpose self-hosted change-monitoring tools like Distill.io or Visualping that can also be configured to watch prices but are not purpose-built for retail price tracking. Discount Bandit's target users are primarily privacy-conscious deal hunters, home-lab and self-hosting enthusiasts who already run other self-hosted infrastructure such as Docker-based media servers or notification stacks, and developers who prefer full control and transparency over the software monitoring their shopping habits rather than depending on a black-box commercial service. Because the project is open source and self-hosted only, it does not offer a managed cloud version, a mobile app beyond the browser extension, or a formal support contract; support instead happens through GitHub Discussions and community contributions, which is typical of small independent open-source tools in this space.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '09c39a74-1b42-4789-af73-47c7785446b4';

