-- ── Django-CRM ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source, self-hosted CRM built on the Django framework for managing leads, deals, tasks, and email marketing without per-user licensing fees.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Independent open-source project (maintainer plus community contributors)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Russian$q$, $q$Ukrainian$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Django-CRM Review 2026: Free Self-Hosted CRM Software$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Django-CRM is a free, open-source, self-hosted CRM built on Django for leads, deals, and email marketing. See features, licensing, pros, cons, and use cases.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Django-CRM (published at DjangoCRM.github.io and hosted in the GitHub repository DjangoCRM/django-crm) is a free, open-source customer relationship management application built directly on the Django web framework and its built-in admin interface. The project is authored and maintained primarily by Vadym Kharchenko, whose copyright notice appears on the project's documentation covering 2024 through 2026, and it is distributed under the GNU Affero General Public License version 3 (AGPL-3.0), a copyleft license that requires any modified version of the software used to provide a network service to also make its source code available. It is worth noting for clarity that several unrelated open-source projects share the generic name 'Django-CRM' on GitHub, including a separate CRM built with Django REST Framework and SvelteKit maintained by MicroPyramid; the project referenced by the DjangoCRM.github.io website and the DjangoCRM GitHub organization is the Kharchenko-maintained system described here, distinct from those other repositories despite the similar naming. Rather than building a custom frontend framework or a novel architecture, Django-CRM leans heavily on Django's own admin interface as its foundation, which is a deliberate design decision that makes the system fast to customize and extend for developers who are already familiar with Django, while keeping the codebase relatively lean compared to CRMs that ship a fully separate custom UI layer. The project describes its status as production and stable, stating that it has been used in real business environments for a number of years, which distinguishes it from many smaller hobbyist open-source CRM projects that never progress past an early or experimental stage. Functionally, Django-CRM covers the core workflows expected of a general-purpose CRM: contact and company record management, sales pipeline and deal or opportunity tracking, task and project management tied to sales activities, built-in mass email marketing and mailing-list functionality (an unusually strong feature for an open-source CRM, since many competitors require a separate email marketing tool), analytics and reporting dashboards for sales performance, role-based access control with configurable permissions for different user types, integrated email and VoIP communication tools so that outbound calls and emails can be logged against the relevant contact or deal automatically, and advanced search filters with data pagination for navigating larger datasets. The platform also supports more than 20 languages, reflecting an internationally distributed user base, with translated documentation available in languages including French and Italian in addition to English. Because Django-CRM is fully open source with no license fees and no per-user costs, businesses that adopt it retain complete ownership of both their codebase and their customer data, avoiding the vendor lock-in that is common with proprietary SaaS CRMs where switching providers can mean losing access to historical data or having to pay for data export. This makes Django-CRM particularly attractive to organizations, especially those staffed by developers comfortable with Python and Django, that want a CRM they can deeply customize to match unusual internal workflows without waiting on a vendor's roadmap or paying for custom development inside a closed commercial platform. The tradeoff is that Django-CRM does not offer any official managed cloud or SaaS hosting option; every deployment is self-hosted, meaning the adopting organization is responsible for provisioning a server, installing dependencies, configuring the database, and handling ongoing maintenance, security patching, and backups themselves, which requires a baseline level of technical capability that non-technical small businesses may not have in-house. The project is documented using Material for MkDocs and is also distributed via the Python Package Index as the django-crm-admin package and mirrored on SourceForge, giving developers multiple installation paths depending on their preferred workflow. Within the broader CRM software landscape, Django-CRM competes most directly with other open-source, self-hosted CRM platforms such as SuiteCRM, EspoCRM, Odoo's CRM module, and the more modern Twenty CRM, as well as, indirectly, with the separately maintained MicroPyramid Django-CRM project that shares only its name. For organizations willing to trade the convenience of a managed SaaS platform for full data ownership and unlimited customization, it also stands as a free alternative to commercial subscription CRMs like HubSpot, Pipedrive, and Salesforce, particularly for smaller businesses, freelancers, or agencies that find per-seat SaaS CRM pricing difficult to justify at their scale and that have, or can access, the Python and Django expertise needed to install, configure, and maintain a self-hosted system over time. Deployment typically follows standard Django conventions, meaning teams provision a server with Python and a supported relational database such as PostgreSQL or MySQL, install the package via pip or clone the repository directly from GitHub, run the standard Django migration commands to build out the schema, and then configure environment variables for email sending, VoIP integration, and any third-party services the business wants to connect. Because the system is built on Django rather than a bespoke framework, it also benefits indirectly from the enormous surrounding Django ecosystem of well-documented third-party packages, security patches, and hosting guides, which lowers the operational risk of running a self-hosted CRM compared to adopting a much smaller, less-documented open-source framework. The project's AGPL-3.0 license is also worth understanding in more detail for prospective adopters: unlike the more permissive MIT or Apache licenses, AGPL-3.0 specifically closes the so-called network-use loophole present in the plain GPL, meaning that if an organization modifies Django-CRM and offers it as a hosted service to others, it must also release the modified source code, a requirement that mainly matters for companies considering reselling a customized version of the CRM as their own SaaS product rather than simply using it internally for their own sales operations.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'cb776dbd-be66-4afc-b3df-cfd58e6b6dd3';

