-- ── Docassemble ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source expert-system platform for building guided interviews and automated legal document assembly, widely used by legal aid organizations and courts.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Independent open-source project (community-maintained)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Docassemble Review 2026: Free Legal Document Automation$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Docassemble is a free, open-source platform for guided interviews and legal document assembly, created by lawyer-programmer Jonathan Pyle in 2015.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Docassemble is a free, open-source expert-system platform for building guided interviews that can generate documents, submit applications, or provide information, one question at a time. It was created by Jonathan Pyle, a Philadelphia-based lawyer and programmer, and was first announced publicly in 2015 at the Legal Services Corporation's Technology Initiative Grant (TIG) conference, an annual gathering focused on technology for legal aid and access-to-justice work; the project has since marked roughly a decade of continuous development and adoption. Pyle originally built docassemble to automate specific legal procedures he encountered in his own practice, and the tool has grown from that legal-aid-focused starting point into a general-purpose guided-interview engine used well beyond the legal sector, though law remains its dominant use case and community. Despite its name emphasizing document assembly, the docassemble documentation is explicit that interviews built on the platform do not need to produce a document at all; an interview can instead submit an application, direct a user to other resources, store structured input for later use, interact with external APIs, or simply present the user with tailored information based on their answers, making it more accurately described as a general expert-system and guided-workflow engine that happens to excel at document generation as one of its capabilities. Technically, docassemble is a Python-based server application in which developers author interviews as YAML documents broken into discrete blocks separated by --- record separators; these blocks can include question blocks that define what is shown to the end user, code blocks written in ordinary Python for logic and calculations, and blocks that define structured data using objects, lists, dictionaries, and groups, giving developers a full programming language's worth of expressiveness alongside a declarative interview-definition format. Interviews can call external APIs, integrate with document templates (using Markdown and Jinja2-style templating to generate Word and PDF output), and can be organized into reusable, shareable units called Packages, which developers commonly publish and version-control on GitHub and can install onto any docassemble server, closely mirroring how software packages are distributed in the broader open-source ecosystem. Docassemble supports flexible deployment options: it can be run locally on a developer's own laptop for building and testing interviews, or deployed to production using Docker containers, and documentation and community guides commonly reference deployment on cloud infrastructure providers such as Amazon Web Services and DigitalOcean; for larger-scale deployments, docassemble supports multi-server and clustered configurations to handle higher interview volumes. The platform is licensed permissively: its source code is released under the MIT license, one of the most permissive open-source licenses available, allowing essentially unrestricted reuse, modification, and even commercial resale, while its documentation is released under a Creative Commons Attribution license (CC BY 3.0). This permissive licensing, combined with the project's origin inside the legal aid community, has helped docassemble become one of the most widely adopted tools in the access-to-justice technology space; it is used by legal aid organizations, courts, law school clinics, government agencies, and corporate legal and compliance departments to build self-service tools that guide non-lawyers or clients through legal processes, generate court forms, or automate contract creation. Suffolk University Law School's Legal Innovation and Technology (LIT) Lab is a particularly active contributor to the docassemble ecosystem, publishing documentation, training materials, and tooling; the LIT Lab has recently worked on incorporating large language model assistance directly into the interview-editing process, reflecting the broader trend of AI-assisted development spreading into even long-established open-source legal technology projects. Because docassemble itself is free and does not offer an official managed hosting service run by its original creator, a surrounding commercial ecosystem of consultants, implementation specialists, and hosting providers has emerged to support organizations that want professional help building interviews or running production servers; firms describing themselves as docassemble experts or developers offer paid implementation, customization, and hosting services built entirely around the free open-source core, similar to how commercial support ecosystems have grown around other major open-source projects like WordPress or Linux distributions. Docassemble's most direct competitors are other document assembly and guided-interview platforms serving the legal industry, including Gavel (formerly Documate), HotDocs, Neota Logic, and ContractExpress; docassemble differentiates itself from all of these primarily by being fully free and open source, whereas its named competitors are commercial products with per-seat or per-document licensing costs. Its target users, correspondingly, are organizations and individuals with the technical capacity (or budget to hire a consultant with that capacity) to write YAML and Python, and who prioritize the flexibility, cost savings, and transparency of a fully open codebase over the more polished, no-code-oriented user experience offered by commercial alternatives aimed at less technical legal teams. A typical docassemble deployment runs as a Python-based web server, most commonly containerized with Docker so that the application, its dependencies, and a supporting database can be brought up consistently across development, staging, and production environments; larger implementations, such as statewide court-forms initiatives or large legal aid organizations serving many users simultaneously, often run docassemble across a small cluster of servers behind a load balancer to handle concurrent interview sessions reliably. Because interviews are plain-text YAML files that can be version-controlled like any other code, docassemble deployments fit naturally into standard software development workflows, including code review, automated testing of interview logic, and continuous deployment pipelines, which is unusual among no-code or low-code legal automation tools and is part of why docassemble has remained popular with more technically sophisticated legal innovation teams even as newer, more polished commercial no-code competitors have entered the market. The project's decade of continued maintenance, an active user forum, and regular conference presence at events focused on access-to-justice technology have also helped it remain the de facto reference implementation that newer legal document automation tools, including some commercial ones, are frequently benchmarked against.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c386a7f9-0f7e-468a-84bc-c61cc73cf1a4';

